## Summary

# Meeting Overview & Attendance

- A brief go-live checkpoint meeting was held to assess the status of the Vacancy and Waitlist Management system deployment, with key participants including Robert, Jess, Stephanie, Nerissa, and others joining the call.
- Syndi was noted to be in training and was absent from the call; the team proceeded without her.
- The tone of the meeting was generally positive, with no major production blockers reported at the outset, and the overall consensus was that the go-live had gone relatively well.

# Waitlist Data Import & Conversion Results

- Robert reported that just under 2,000 waitlist episodes were successfully imported during the conversion, with the count having grown to 2,014 by the time of the meeting, indicating that users were actively engaging with the system.
- Of the remaining approximately 500 records that were not imported, around 300 were in a "Recommended" status, meaning they require annual review as these clients often will not ultimately make it onto the waitlist.
- The remaining ~200 unimported records broke down into two groups: approximately 100 were rejected due to locked client charts at the time of import, and the other ~100 failed due to missing case managers in home or supportive living episodes, assigned pools, missing home/supportive living episodes entirely, or unpopulated/invalid responsible zones such as Emerson and Calgary — all of which will require manual review.
# Post-Go-Live Issues & Support Tickets

- One support ticket was received from the Terrace team, who incorrectly expected that a Plan of Care would be automatically created for clients during the conversion process; this was identified as a training and communication gap rather than a system defect.
- Additional support tickets were anticipated throughout the day as more users began accessing the system and encountered workflows they were unfamiliar with.
- Robert noted he was monitoring incoming issues and planned to investigate further, while the team acknowledged that most early-day concerns were likely to be training-related misunderstandings.

# Playground & Training Environment Problems

- Significant issues were reported in the playground (PLY) and ACEs training environments, where a Plan of Care error was surfacing stating that the episode was "not linked" even when it was in fact linked, preventing users from starting or working with any Plan of Care.
- Karen had attempted a fix in the REF environment with the expectation that it would propagate to PLY, but it did not appear to have pushed down successfully, leaving the root cause unclear — whether REF failed to refresh or another issue was at play.
- An emergency ticket was submitted by Diane to move content from MST to the playground environment; it was unclear whether the same issue existed in MST, and further investigation was planned to determine the full scope of the problem.

# Edmonton Zone Concern & Production Verification

- During the meeting, Jess received an email from the Edmonton Zone via Janette claiming that the waitlist episode was not live in production, prompting immediate attention from the team.
    
- The team's working theory was that this was a misunderstanding — specifically, that Edmonton Zone users may have been confusing the non-functional playground environment with the production environment, rather than experiencing an actual production outage.
    
- Diane was actively verifying the production environment to confirm the system was functioning as expected, and the team noted that other users were already successfully accessing the waitlist episode in production, supporting the misunderstanding hypothesis.
    

# Communication & Messaging Plan

- A memo was planned to communicate key conversion outcomes to stakeholders, covering what was successfully converted, what requires manual follow-up, and clarification that Plans of Care are not automatically created during conversion.
    
- The memo will also include guidance on where to find relevant reports and reinforce updated workflows, specifically that users should now be using the Plan of Care for any updates going forward.
    
- Leadership was identified as a key channel for reinforcing these messages, and the communications were intended to proactively address the kinds of misunderstandings already surfacing, such as the Terrace team's ticket.
    

# Next Steps & Follow-Up Actions

- Robert to continue investigating additional reporting options to allow tracking of whether clients on the waitlist have a corresponding waitlist episode, and to follow up on the PLY environment fix that did not propagate from REF.
    
- Jess to investigate the Edmonton Zone concern and flag to the team immediately if a confirmed production issue is identified, at which point the group agreed to reconvene via a huddle flagged in the meeting chat.
    
- Diane to continue verifying production environment stability, and the full team to monitor incoming support tickets throughout the day to identify any patterns pointing to systemic issues versus isolated training gaps.